  "prompt": "When is it likely that the proposed extended maternity leave from 12 to 26 weeks will be implemented for private sectors in India?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, the Government of India has proposed amending the Maternity Benefit Act to extend maternity leave for women in the private sector from the current 12 weeks to 26 weeks. This proposal aims to provide greater support to working mothers and is part of broader efforts to improve workplace policies related to parental leave.\n\n**Current Status:**\n- **Cabinet Approval:** The Cabinet of India has approved the amendment to extend maternity leave.\n- **Legislative Process:** The proposed changes still need to be debated and passed by the Parliament before they can be officially implemented.\n\n**Expected Timeline:**\n- **Parliamentary Approval:** Assuming the amendment proceeds smoothly through both houses of Parliament without significant delays, it is plausible that the extended maternity leave could be legislated within the latter part of 2023 or early 2024.\n- **Implementation:** Once the amendment is passed by Parliament and receives the necessary certifications, it would typically take a few months for the new provisions to be integrated into the existing framework and for businesses to comply with the updated requirements. Therefore, widespread implementation in the private sector could likely occur in mid to late 2024.\n\n**Factors Influencing the Timeline:**\n- **Legislative Agenda:** The speed at which Parliament addresses the amendment will play a crucial role. If there is broad consensus and prioritization, the process will be expedited.\n- **Administrative Preparations:** The government and relevant departments will need time to update guidelines, inform businesses, and possibly conduct awareness campaigns to ensure smooth adoption of the new policy.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nWhile the exact date remains uncertain, the extension of maternity leave from 12 to 26 weeks for the private sector in India is expected to be implemented in 2024, contingent upon successful passage through the legislative process and subsequent administrative preparations.",
